ce:section.ce:para:
The in-situ synthesized GQDs were collected through removing the LTbH layers with acid corrosion and characterized by TEM (Fig. 2
                     ), which shows obvious lattice fringes with distance of 0.21 nm (inset in Fig. 2 A) corresponding to (100) plane of graphene [16]. The sizes of the GQDs were about 5–6 nm as labeled by the circles in Fig. 2 A. Fig. 2 B is an enlarged view of the GQD shown in Fig. 2 A, in which the well-identified hexagonal lattice structure of graphene is visible, and some defects and distortions are marked in the red circle. The latter should be induced by the existence of heteroatom oxygen atoms linked on the carbon skeleton, presented in Fig. 3
                      B and Fig. S2. The elemental mappings from a GQD-LTbH nanosheet (Fig. 2C) show homogeneous distribution of C and Tb in the in-plane LTbH (Fig. 2 D and E). These in-situ synthesized GQDs could further be demonstrated by the SAED in Fig. S3, which showed the diffraction spots/rings of (110) and (100) planes of graphene.
